# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: prime-editing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] In genetics, a **deletion** (also called **gene deletion**, **deficiency**, or **deletion mutation**) (sign: Δ) is a mutation (a genetic aberration) in which a part of a chromosome or a sequence of DNA is left out during DNA replication.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Any number of nucleotides can be deleted, from a single base to an entire piece of chromosome.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Some chromosomes have fragile spots where breaks occur, which result in the **deletion** of a part of the chromosome.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] The breaks can be induced by heat, viruses, radiation, or chemical reactions.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] When a chromosome breaks, if a part of it is deleted or lost, the missing piece of chromosome is referred to as a deletion or a deficiency.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] For synapsis to occur between a chromosome with a large intercalary deficiency and a normal complete homolog, the unpaired region of the normal homolog must loop out of the linear structure into a **deletion** or **compensation loop**.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] The smallest single base deletion mutations occur by a single base flipping in the template DNA, followed by template DNA strand slippage, within the DNA polymerase active site.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletions can be caused by errors in chromosomal crossover during meiosis, which causes several serious genetic diseases.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletions that do not occur in multiples of three bases can cause a frameshift by changing the 3-nucleotide protein reading frame of the genetic sequence.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletions are representative of eukaryotic organisms, including humans and not in prokaryotic organisms, such as bacteria.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Micro-deletion is usually found in children with physical abnormalities.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] A large amount of deletion would result in immediate abortion (miscarriage).
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] The International System for Human Cytogenomic Nomenclature (ISCN) is an international standard for human chromosome nomenclature, which includes band names, symbols and abbreviated terms used in the description of human chromosome and chromosome abnormalities.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Abbreviations include a minus sign (−) for chromosome deletions, and *del* for deletions of parts of a chromosome.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Small deletions are less likely to be fatal; large deletions are usually fatal – there are always variations based on which genes are lost.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Some medium-sized deletions lead to recognizable human disorders, e.g.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletion of a number of pairs that is not evenly divisible by three will lead to a frameshift mutation, causing all of the codons occurring after the deletion to be read incorrectly during translation, producing a severely altered and potentially nonfunctional protein.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] In contrast, a deletion that is evenly divisible by three is called an *in-frame* deletion.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletions are responsible for an array of genetic disorders, including some cases of male infertility, two thirds of cases of Duchenne muscular dystrophy, and two thirds of cases of cystic fibrosis (those caused by ΔF508).
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletion of part of the short arm of chromosome 5 results in Cri du chat syndrome.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Deletions in the SMN-encoding gene cause spinal muscular atrophy, the most common genetic cause of infant death.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Microdeletions are associated with many different conditions, including Angelman syndrome, Prader-Willi syndrome, and DiGeorge syndrome.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Some syndromes, including Angelman syndrome and Prader-Willi syndrome, are associated with both microdeletions and genomic imprinting, meaning that same microdeletion can cause two different syndromes depending on which parent the deletion came from.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Recent work suggests that some deletions of highly conserved sequences (CONDELs) may be responsible for the evolutionary differences present among closely related species.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Such deletions in humans, referred to as hCONDELs, may be responsible for the anatomical and behavioral differences between humans, chimpanzees and other varieties of mammals like ape or monkeys.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Recent comprehensive patient-level classification and quantification of driver events in TCGA cohorts revealed that there are on average 12 driver events per tumor, of which 2.1 are deletions of tumor suppressors.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] The introduction of molecular techniques in conjunction with classical cytogenetic methods has in recent years greatly improved the diagnostic potential for chromosomal abnormalities.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] In particular, microarray-comparative genomic hybridization (CGH) based on the use of BAC clones promises a sensitive strategy for the detection of DNA copy-number changes on a genome-wide scale.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] The resolution of detection could be as high as >30,000 "bands" and the size of chromosomal deletion detected could as small as 5–20 kb in length.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Other computation methods were selected to discover DNA sequencing deletion errors such as end-sequence profiling.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] In the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*, the nuclear genes *Rad51*p, *Rad52*p and *Rad59p* encode proteins that are necessary for recombinational repair and are employed in the repair of double strand breaks in mitochondrial DNA.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] Loss of these proteins decreases the rate of spontaneous DNA deletion events in mitochondria.
[src:prime-editing/deletion-genetics] This finding implies that the repair of DNA double-strand breaks by homologous recombination is a step in the formation of mitochondrial DNA deletions.
[src:prime-editing/flap-endonuclease] The endonuclease activity of FENs was initially identified as acting on a DNA duplex which has a single-stranded 5' overhang on one of the strands (termed a "5' flap", hence the name flap endonuclease).
[src:prime-editing/flap-endonuclease] FENs catalyse hydrolytic cleavage of the phosphodiester bond at the junction of single- and double-stranded DNA.
[src:prime-editing/flap-endonuclease] Some FENs can also act as 5'-3' exonucleases on the 5' terminus of the flap strand and on 'nicked' DNA substrates.
[src:prime-editing/flap-endonuclease] Protein structure models based on X-ray crystallography data suggest that FENs have a flexible arch created by two α-helices through which the single 5' strand of the 5' flap structure can thread.
[src:prime-editing/flap-endonuclease] Flap endonucleases have been used in biotechnology, for example the Taqman PCR assay and the Invader Assay for mutation and single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) detection.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] In genetics, an **insertion** (also called an **insertion mutation**) is the addition of one or more nucleotide base pairs into a DNA sequence.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] This can often happen in microsatellite regions due to the DNA polymerase slipping.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Insertions can be anywhere in size from one base pair incorrectly inserted into a DNA sequence to a section of one chromosome inserted into another.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] The mechanism of the smallest single base insertion mutations is believed to be through base-pair separation between the template and primer strands followed by non-neighbor base stacking, which can occur locally within the DNA polymerase active site.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] On a chromosome level, an *insertion* refers to the insertion of a larger sequence into a chromosome.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] This can happen due to unequal crossover during meiosis.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Trinucleotide repeats are classified as insertion mutations and sometimes as a separate class of mutations.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Zinc finger nuclease (ZFN), Transcription activator-like effector nucleases (TALEN), and CRISPR gene editing are the three main methods used in the former research to achieve gene insertion.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] And CRISPR/Cas tools have already become one of the most used methods to present research.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Based on CRISPR/Cas tools, different systems have already been developed to achieve specific functions.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] For example, one strategy is double-strand nucleases cutting system, using the normal Cas9 protein with single guide RNA (sgRNA) and then achieving the gene insertion through end-joining or dividing cells with the DNA repair system.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Another example is the prime editing system, which uses Cas9 nickase and the prime editing guide RNA (pegRNA) carrying the target genes.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] One limitation of current technology is that the size for DNA precise insertion is not large enough to meet the demand for genome research.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] RNA-guided DNA transposition is an emerging area to solve this problem.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] More efficient methods are expected to be developed and applied in the genome engineering area.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Insertions can be particularly hazardous if they occur in an exon, the amino acid coding region of a gene.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] A frameshift mutation, an alteration in the normal reading frame of a gene, results if the number of inserted nucleotides is not divisible by three, i.e., the number of nucleotides per codon.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Frameshift mutations will alter all the amino acids encoded by the gene following the mutation.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Usually, insertions and the subsequent frameshift mutation will cause the active translation of the gene to encounter a premature stop codon, resulting in an end to translation and the production of a truncated protein.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] Transcripts carrying the frameshift mutation may also be degraded through Nonsense-mediated decay during translation, thus not resulting in any protein product.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] If translated, the truncated proteins frequently are unable to function properly or at all and can result in any number of genetic disorders depending on the gene in which the insertion occurs.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] In-frame insertions occur when the reading frame is not altered as a result of the insertion; the number of inserted nucleotides is divisible by three.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] The reading frame remains intact after the insertion and translation will most likely run to completion if the inserted nucleotides do not code for a stop codon.
[src:prime-editing/insertion-genetics] However, because of the inserted nucleotides, the finished protein will contain, depending on the size of the insertion, multiple new amino acids that may affect the function of the protein.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] A **nick** is a discontinuity in a double stranded DNA molecule where there is no phosphodiester bond between adjacent nucleotides of one strand.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] They typically occur through damage or enzyme action.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicks allow DNA strands to untwist during replication, and are also thought to play a role in the DNA mismatch repair mechanisms that fix errors on both the leading and lagging daughter strands.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The diagram shows the effects of nicks on intersecting DNA in a twisted plasmid.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicking can be used to dissipate the energy held up by intersecting states.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The nicks allow the DNA to take on a circular shape.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicked DNA can be the result of DNA damage or purposeful, regulated biomolecular reactions carried out in the cell.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] During processing, DNA can be nicked by physical shearing, over-drying, or enzymes.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Excessive rough handling in pipetting or vortexing creates physical stress that can lead to breaks and nicks in DNA.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Overdrying of DNA can also break the phosphodiester bond in DNA and result in nicks.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicking enzymes can assist with this process.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] A nick in DNA can be formed by the hydrolysis and subsequent removal of a phosphate group within the helical backbone.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] This leads to a different DNA conformation, where a hydrogen bond forms in place of the missing piece of the DNA backbone in order to preserve the structure.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Ligases are versatile and ubiquitous enzymes that join the 3' hydroxyl and 5' phosphate ends to form a phosphodiester bond, making them essential in nicked DNA repair, and ultimately genome fidelity.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] This biological role has also been extremely valuable in sealing the sticky ends of plasmids in molecular cloning.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Their importance is attested by the fact most organisms have multiple ligases dedicated to specific pathways of repairing DNA.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] In eubacteria, these ligases are powered by NAD+ rather than ATP.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Each nick site requires 1 ATP or 1 NAD+ to power the ligase repair.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nick sealing, or phosphodiester bond formation.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] One particular example of a ligase catalyzing nick closure is the *E. coli* NAD+ dependent DNA ligase, LigA.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] LigA is a relevant example as it is structurally similar to a clade of enzymes found across all types of bacteria.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Ligases have a metal binding site which is capable of recognizing nicks in DNA.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The ligase forms a DNA-adenylate complex, assisting recognition.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] With human DNA ligase, this forms a crystallized complex.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The complex, which has a DNA–adenylate intermediate, allows DNA ligase I to institute a conformational change in the DNA for the isolation and subsequent repair of the DNA nick.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Single-stranded nicks act as recognizable markers to help the repair machinery distinguish the newly synthesized strand (daughter strand) from the template strand (parental strand).
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] DNA mismatch repair (MMR) is an important DNA repair system that helps maintain genome plasticity by correcting mismatches, or non Watson-Crick base pairs in a DNA duplex.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Some sources of mismatched base pairs include replication errors and deamination of 5-methylcytosine DNA to form thymine.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] MMR in most bacteria and eukaryotes is directed to the erroneous strand of the mismatched duplex through recognition of strand discontinuities, while MMR in *E. coli* and closely related bacteria is directed to the strand on the basis of the absence of methylation.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicking endonucleases introduce strand discontinuities, or DNA nicks, for both respective systems.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Mut L homologues from eukaryotes and most bacteria incise the discontinuous strand to introduce the entry or termination point for the excision reaction.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Similarly, in *E. coli*, Mut H nicks the unmethylated strand of the duplex to introduce the entry point of excision.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] For eukaryotes specifically, the mechanism of DNA replication elongation between the leading and lagging strand differs.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] On the lagging strand, nicks exist between Okazaki fragments and are easily recognizable by the DNA mismatch repair machinery prior to ligation.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Due to the continuous replication that occurs on the leading strand, the mechanism there is slightly more complex.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] During replication, ribonucleotides are added by replication enzymes and these ribonucleotides are nicked by an enzyme called RNase H2.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Together, the presence of a nick and a ribonucleotide make the leading strand easily recognizable to the DNA mismatch repair machinery.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nick translation is a biological process in which a single-stranded DNA nick serves as the marker for DNA polymerase to excise and replace possibly damaged nucleotides.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] At the end of the segment that DNA polymerase acts on, DNA ligase must repair the final segment of the DNA backbone in order to complete the repair process.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] In a lab setting, this can be used to introduce fluorescent or other tagged nucleotides by purposefully inducing site-specific, single-stranded nicks in DNA in vitro and then adding the nicked DNA to an environment rich in DNA polymerase and tagged nucleotide.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The DNA polymerase then replaces the DNA nucleotides with the tagged ones, starting at the site of the single-stranded nick.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicked DNA plays an important role in many biological functions.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] For instance, single-stranded nicks in DNA may serve as purposeful biological markers for the enzyme topoisomerase that unwinds packed DNA and is critical to DNA replication and transcription.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] In these instances, nicked DNA is not the result of unwanted cell damage.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Topoisomerase-1 preferentially acts at nicks in DNA to cleave adjacent to the nick and then winds or unwinds the complex topologies associated with packed DNA.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Here, the nick in the DNA serves as a marker for single strand breakage and subsequent unwinding.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] It is possible that this is not a highly conserved process.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Topoisomerase may cause short deletions when it cleaves bonds, because both full-length DNA products and short deletion strands are seen as products of topoisomerase cleavage while inactive mutants only produced full-length DNA strands.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicks in DNA also give rise to different structural properties, can be involved in repairing damages caused by ultraviolet radiation, and are used in the primary steps that allow for genetic recombination.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nick idling is a biological process in which DNA polymerase may slow or stop its activity of adding bases to a new daughter strand during DNA replication at a nick site.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] DNA structure changes when a single-stranded nick is introduced.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Stability is decreased as a break in the phosphodiester backbone allows DNA to unwind, as the built up stress from twisting and packing is not being resisted as strongly anymore.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Nicked DNA is more susceptible to degradation due to this reduced stability.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The ***nic* site** or nick region is found within the **origin of transfer** (*oriT*) site and is a key in starting bacterial conjugation.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] A single strand of DNA, called the **T-strand**, is cut at *nic* by an enzyme called relaxase.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] This single strand is eventually transferred to the recipient cell during the process of bacterial conjugation.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Before this cleavage can occur, however, it is necessary for a group of proteins to attach to the *oriT* site.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] This group of proteins is called the relaxosome.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] It is thought that portions of the *oriT* site are bent in a way that creates interaction between the relaxosome proteins and the *nic* site.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] Cleaving the T-strand involves relaxase cutting a phosphodiester bond at the nic site.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] The cleaved strand is left with a hydroxyl group at the 3' end, which may allow for the strand to form a circular plasmid after moving into the recipient cell.
[src:prime-editing/nick-dna] DNA nicks promote crossover formation during meiosis, and such nicks are protected from ligation by Exonuclease 1 (Exo1).
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The technology has received mainstream press attention due to its potential uses in medical genetics.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] It utilizes methodologies similar to precursor genome editing technologies, including CRISPR/Cas9 and Base editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editing has been used on some animal models of genetic disease, in various plants, and in bacteria.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The first human trials for happened in 2024, with both patients enlisted being effectively cured of chronic granulomatous disease.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Genomic editing takes place by transfecting cells with the pegRNA and the fusion protein.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Transfection is often accomplished by introducing vectors into a cell.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Once internalized, the fusion protein nicks the target DNA sequence, exposing a 3'-hydroxyl group that can be used to initiate (prime) the reverse transcription of the RT template portion of the pegRNA.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This results in a branched intermediate that contains two DNA flaps: a 3' flap that contains the newly synthesized (edited) sequence, and a 5' flap that contains the dispensable, unedited DNA sequence.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The 5' flap is then cleaved by structure-specific endonucleases or 5' exonucleases.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This process allows 3' flap ligation, and creates a heteroduplex DNA composed of one edited strand and one unedited strand.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The reannealed double stranded DNA contains nucleotide mismatches at the location where editing took place.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Despite its increased efficacy, the edit installed by PE2 might still be removed by mismatch repair of the edited strand.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] To counter this, the Prime Editor 3 strategy comes with an extra component borrowed from base editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In addition to the editor itself, PE3 uses a standard Cas9 nickase to exploit DNA repair systems by targeting the opposite non-edited strand.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Following the nick on the non-edited strand, DNA repair will use the edited strand as a template, consequentially improving the odds of success.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, there are drawbacks to this system as the unaltered strand can be nicked prematurely and lead to additional undesired indels.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editor 4 utilizes the same machinery as PE2, but also includes a plasmid that encodes for dominant negative MMR protein MLH1.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Dominant negative MLH1 is able to essentially knock out endogenous MLH1 by inhibition, thereby reducing cellular MMR response and increasing prime editing efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editor 5 utilizes the same machinery as PE3, but also includes a plasmid that encodes for dominant negative MLH1.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Like PE4, this allows for a knockdown of endogenous MMR response, increasing the efficiency of prime editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The "twin prime editing" (twinPE) mechanism reported in 2021 allows editing large sequences of DNA – sequences as large as genes – which addresses the method's key drawback.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] It uses a prime editor protein and two prime editing guide RNAs.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editing efficiency can be increased with the use of engineered pegRNAs (epegRNAs).
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] One common issue with traditional pegRNAs is degradation of the 3' end, leading to decreased PE efficiency. epegRNAs have a structured RNA motif added to their 3' end to prevent degradation.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Xr-pegRNA is similar to epegRNA in that it adds an additional RNA motif after the primer binding sequence.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In this case, these are Xrn1-resistant RNAs (xrRNAs), a group of conserved knot-like structures found in flaviviruses.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] They impede viral RNA degradation and are highly resistant to unfolding.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This finding was consistent across different genes and cell types.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Though using a xrRNA-PE3 strategy generally improved efficiency, there were a few sites where xr-PE2 barely differed from xr-PE3.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In terms of which xrRNA motif worked best, the exact answer varied by target.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, the Zika motif functioned generally well for both PE2 and PE3 strategies.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Compared to epegRNA, xr-pegRNA has a similar edit-to-indel ratio and improvement in efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, unlike the RNA pseudoknot from the Moloney murine leukemia virus (mpknot), xr-pegRNA doesn't need an RNA linker to ensure structural stability.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This is similar to the evopreQ1 motif, though even that sometimes requires one.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Because the linker isn't necessary, using xr-pegRNA would offer better predictability and could prove more convenient.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editing was developed in the lab of David R.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Liu at the Broad Institute and disclosed in Anzalone et al.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Since then prime editing and the research that produced it have received widespread scientific acclaim, being called "revolutionary" and an important part of the future of editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] During the development of this technology, several modifications were done to the components, in order to increase its effectiveness.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editor 1 was a prototype designed to have the minimum components necessary.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] It consisted of a wild-type Moloney murine leukemia virus (MMLV) reverse transcriptase attached to Cas9 H840A nickase by a flexible protein linker.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Originally, the linker was too short and the reverse transcriptase was unable to do its job.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, extending it to 8-15 bases led to detectable editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] During development, the linker was attached to either the C- or N-terminal of the Cas9 protein.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Linkage the C terminal proved more efficient, so it was chosen as the final design.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Detectable editing efficiencies were observed.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] After the success of PE1, researchers chose to modify its reverse transcriptase.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This was done to improve DNA synthesis and thus the editor's overall efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] They started by searching the literature for previously described mutations.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] These were found to improve the enzyme's thermostability, processivity, DNA to RNA substrate affinity, or prevent interference by RNaseH.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] A variety of mutations were combined into nineteen different variants and then tested against each other in human cells.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Researchers began by focusing on thermal stability.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] They found that a reverse transcriptase combining D200N, L603W, and T330P mutations improved editing efficiency by an average of 6.8-fold for insertions and transversions at five different sites.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Following this, the mutant transcriptase was further combined with additional mutations.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Adding T306K and W313F improved editing efficiency by an additional 1.3 to 3-fold for insertions or transversions at the same five sites.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The resulting prime editor was deemed PE2.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime Editor 2 had a substantially higher efficiency than its predecessor when making insertion, deletion, or substitution mutations.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Additionally, it was compatible with a shorter primer binding site (PBS) sequence due to its enhanced substrate affinity.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Nuclease Prime Editor uses Cas9 nuclease instead of Cas9(H840A) nickase.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Unlike prime editor 3 (PE3) that requires dual-nick at both DNA strands to induce efficient prime editing, Nuclease Prime Editor requires only a single pegRNA since the single-gRNA already creates double-strand break instead of single-strand nick.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] PEmax was created to further enhance the improvements made in PE2.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] To do this, researchers tested twenty-one PE2 variants with different Cas9 mutations, reverse transcriptase codon usages, nuclear localization sequences (NLS), protein linker lengths, and protein linker compositions.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Afterwards, the resulting protein (dubbed PEmax) was pitted against other improved prime editors.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] All were tested on HeLa cells and performed various modifications at seven genomic sites.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Notable competitors included PE2*, which has additional NLS sequences, and CMP–PE–V1, which contains high-mobility peptides.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] PEmax outperformed both at 6/7 sites, with the time it lost to PE2* being within the margin of error.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] While improvements vary by cell line and modification, PEmax can be combined with various strategies (PE2max, PE3max, PE4max, PE5max) as well as epegRNA to dramatically enhance editing efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, note that combining PEmax with PE3 or PE5 leads to a slight increase in indels.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This is likely due to the editor's increased nicking ability.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] At the time this development was published, most prime editor variants used a SpCas9 H840A nickase.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] One issue with this protein is that the Cas9 from *Streptococcus pyogenes* can only nick 3 to 4 bases upstream from the PAM, thus limiting the editor's potential.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] As a workaround, one group made a prime editor using a Cas9 ortholog from *Francisella novicida*.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This protein has the same NGG PAM as SpCas9 but different cleavage properties.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] On the target strand (the DNA where the guide RNA binds) FnCas9 makes a cut 3 base pairs upstream the PAM, just like SpCas9.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, on the non-target strand, this protein cleaves 6 to 8 bases upstream.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] By changing the 969th histidine to an alanine, FnCas9 can be converted into a H969A nickase and will only snip the non-target strand.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The primer becomes smaller, but the reverse transcriptase template gains an expanded editing range.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Starting off, researchers fused the FnCas9 nickase with a MMLV reverse transcriptase (RT) from a standard PE2 prime editor.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] They then attempted to optimize it by testing different linker lengths for both the pegRNA (extra nucleotides between the RNA scaffold and reverse transcriptase template) and the protein (amino acids between the Cas9 and RT).
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] It turned out that a protein with a 1x linker (of unknown size) and a normal pegRNA (no linkers at all) worked best.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Next, the group used a PE3 strategy to insert two thymines (TT) into various genes.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] They did this to check how primer binding sequence (PBS) and reverse transcriptase template (RTT) lengths affected efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In general, having a longer PBS made the editor more efficient.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The RTT length had an effect, but there was no consistent pattern.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Furthermore, the insertion efficiency significantly differed for each gene depending on where the extra PE3 guide RNA nicked.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Comparing the two Cas9s, the one from *Francisella novicida* had more variation in efficiency and was overall worse than the one from *Streptococcus pyogenes* (3.82-87.56% vs 29.34-95.18%) when using a PE3 strategy.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] That might've been due to FnCas9's weaker nicking ability, something found in another experiment.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] To compensate, the group created a new strategy deemed PE4.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Details on this can be found in the Editing mechanism section.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Using previous research, the same group engineered a FnCas9 prime editor with a relaxed PAM-recognition site.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Mutating the 1369th glutamic acid to arginine (E1369R), 1449th glutamic acid to histidine (E1449H), and 1556th argenine to alanine (R1556A) generates a Cas9 that recognizes a YG PAM.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This RHA-FnCas9 is capable of targeting sequences ending in TG or CG (something SpCas9 can't do) and further expands the editor's range of targets.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] PE is among recently introduced technologies which allow the transfer of single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) from one individual crop plant to another.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] PE is precise enough to be used to recreate an arbitrary SNP in an arbitrary target, including deletions, insertions, and all 12 point mutations without also needing to perform a double-stranded break or carry a donating template.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In 2024, PM359, a gene therapy developed by Prime Medicine, became the first prime editor to enter clinical trials for human use.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime Medicine reported in December 2025 that two chronic granulomatous disease patients treated with PM359 had been "effectively cured" of the disease.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editors may be used in gene drives.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] A prime editor may be incorporated into the *Cleaver* half of a *Cleave and Rescue* *ClvR* system.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] In this case it is not meant to perform a precise alteration but instead to merely disrupt.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Base editors used for prime editing require delivery of both a protein and RNA molecule into living cells.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Introducing exogenous gene editing technologies into living organisms is a significant challenge.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] One potential way to introduce a base editor into animals and plants is to package the base editor into a viral capsid.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The target organism can then be transduced by the virus to synthesize the base editor *in vivo*.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Common laboratory vectors of transduction such as lentivirus cause immune responses in humans, so proposed human therapies often centered around adeno-associated virus (AAV) because AAV infections are largely asymptomatic.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Unfortunately, the effective packaging capacity of AAV vectors is small, approximately 4.4kb not including inverted terminal repeats.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] As a comparison, an SpCas9-reverse transcriptase fusion protein is 6.3kb, which does not even account for the lengthened guide RNA necessary for targeting and priming the site of interest.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, successful delivery in mice has been achieved by splitting the editor into two AAV vectors or by using an adenovirus, which has a larger packaging capacity.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Although additional research is required to improve the efficiency of prime editing, the technology offers promising scientific improvements over other gene editing tools.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The prime editing technology has the potential to correct the vast majority of pathogenic alleles that cause genetic diseases, as it can repair insertions, deletions, and nucleotide substitutions.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The prime editing tool offers advantages over traditional gene editing technologies.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] CRISPR/Cas9 edits rely on double-strand breaks and non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) or homology-directed repair (HDR) to fix DNA breaks, while the prime editing system employs single-strand breaks and DNA mismatch repair.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] This is an important feature of this technology given that DNA repair mechanisms such as NHEJ and HDR, generate unwanted, random insertions or deletions (indels).
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] These are byproducts that complicate the retrieval of cells carrying the correct edit.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editors do not frequently create these indel byproducts, suggesting that prime editors can be more precise than earlier tools.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] The prime editing system introduces single-stranded DNA breaks, as with base editors, instead of the double-stranded DNA breaks observed in other editing tools, such as CRISPR/Cas9 editing.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Collectively, base editing and prime editing offer complementary strengths and weaknesses for making targeted transition mutations.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Base editors offer higher editing efficiency and fewer indel byproducts if the desired edit is a transition point mutation and a PAM sequence exists roughly 15 bases from the target site.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, because the prime editing technology does not require a precisely positioned PAM sequence to target a nucleotide sequence, it offers more flexibility and editing precision.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Remarkably, prime editors allow all types of substitutions, both transitions and transversions, to be installed into the target sequence.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Cytosine base editing and adenine BE can already perform precise base transitions but base transversions cannot be achieved with these base editors.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editing performs transversions with high efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] PE can insert up to 44bp, delete up to 80, or combinations thereof.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] There is considerable interest in applying gene-editing methods to the treatment of diseases with a genetic component.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] However, there are multiple challenges associated with this approach.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] An effective treatment would require editing of a large number of target cells, which in turn would require an effective method of delivery and a great level of tissue specificity.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] As of 2019, prime editing looks promising for relatively small genetic alterations, but more research needs to be conducted to evaluate whether the technology is efficient in making larger alterations, such as targeted insertions and deletions.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Larger genetic alterations would require a longer RT template, which could hinder the efficient delivery of pegRNA to target cells.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Furthermore, a pegRNA containing a long RT template could become vulnerable to damage caused by cellular enzymes.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Prime editing in plants suffers from low efficiency ranging from zero to a few percent and needs significant improvement.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Some of these limitations have been mitigated by recent improvements to the prime editors, including motifs that protect pegRNAs from degradation.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Further research is needed before prime editing could be used to correct pathogenic alleles in humans.
[src:prime-editing/prime-editing] Research has also shown that inhibition of certain MMR proteins, including MLH1 can improve prime editing efficiency.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] A **reverse transcriptase** (**RT**) is an enzyme that uses an RNA molecule as a template to synthesize a complementary DNA molecule, through a process termed **reverse transcription**.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptases are used by viruses such as HIV and hepatitis B to replicate their genomes, by retrotransposon mobile genetic elements to proliferate within the host genome, and by eukaryotic cells to extend the telomeres at the ends of their linear chromosomes.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The process does not violate the flows of genetic information as described by the classical central dogma, but rather expands it to include transfers of information from RNA to DNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Retroviral RT has three sequential biochemical activities: RNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity, ribonuclease H (RNase H), and DNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Collectively, these activities enable the enzyme to convert single-stranded RNA into double-stranded cDNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In retroviruses and retrotransposons, this cDNA can then be endogenized into the host genome, from which new RNA copies can be made via host-cell transcription.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The same sequence of reactions is widely used in the laboratory to convert RNA to DNA for use in molecular cloning, RNA sequencing, polymerase chain reaction (PCR), or genome analysis.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptases were discovered by Howard Temin at the University of Wisconsin–Madison in *Rous sarcoma* virions and independently isolated by David Baltimore in 1970 at MIT from two RNA tumour viruses: murine leukemia virus and again Rous sarcoma virus.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] For their achievements, they shared the 1975 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine (with Renato Dulbecco).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase was initially called **RNA-dependent DNA polymerase**.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The term "reverse transcriptase" was coined in an anonymous letter to *Nature*, where it appeared as early as August 1970.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The enzymes are encoded and used by viruses that use reverse transcription as a step in the process of replication.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse-transcribing RNA viruses, such as retroviruses, use the enzyme to reverse-transcribe their RNA genomes into DNA, which is then integrated into the host genome and replicated along with it.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse-transcribing DNA viruses, such as the hepadnaviruses, can allow RNA to serve as a template in assembling and making DNA strands.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] HIV infects humans with the use of this enzyme.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Without reverse transcriptase, the viral genome would not be able to incorporate into the host cell, resulting in failure to replicate.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase creates double-stranded DNA from an RNA template.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The process of reverse transcription, also called retrotranscription, is extremely error-prone, and it is during this step that mutations may occur.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Such mutations may cause drug resistance.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Retroviruses, also referred to as class VI ssRNA-RT viruses, are RNA reverse-transcribing viruses with a DNA intermediate.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Their genomes consist of two molecules of positive-sense single-stranded RNA with a 5′ cap and 3′ polyadenylated tail.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Examples of retroviruses include the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and the human T-lymphotropic virus (HTLV).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Lysyl tRNA acts as a primer and hybridizes to a complementary part of the virus RNA genome called the primer binding site or PBS.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase then adds DNA nucleotides onto the 3′ end of the primer, synthesizing DNA complementary to the U5 (non-coding region) and R region (a direct repeat found at both ends of the RNA molecule) of the viral RNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] A domain on the reverse transcriptase enzyme called RNAse H degrades the U5 and R regions on the 5′ end of the RNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The tRNA primer then "jumps" to the 3′ end of the viral genome, and the newly synthesized DNA strands hybridizes to the complementary R region on the RNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The complementary DNA (cDNA) synthesized in (1) is further extended.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The majority of viral RNA is degraded by RNAse H, leaving only the PP sequence.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Synthesis of the second DNA strand begins, using the remaining PP fragment of viral RNA as a primer.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The tRNA primer leaves and a "jump" happens.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The PBS from the second strand hybridizes with the complementary PBS on the first strand.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Both strands are extended to form a complete double-stranded DNA copy of the original viral RNA genome, which can then be incorporated into the host's genome by the enzyme integrase.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Retroviral RNA is arranged in 5′ terminus to 3′ terminus.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The site where the primer is annealed to viral RNA is called the primer-binding site (PBS).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The RNA 5′end to the PBS site is called U5, and the RNA 3′ end to the PBS is called the leader.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The tRNA primer is unwound between 14 and 22 nucleotides and forms a base-paired duplex with the viral RNA at PBS.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The fact that the PBS is located near the 5′ terminus of viral RNA is unusual because reverse transcriptase synthesize DNA from 3′ end of the primer in the 5′ to 3′ direction (with respect to the newly synthesized DNA strand).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Therefore, the primer and reverse transcriptase must be relocated to 3′ end of viral RNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In order to accomplish this reposition, multiple steps and various enzymes including DNA polymerase, ribonuclease H (RNase H) and polynucleotide unwinding are needed.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The HIV reverse transcriptase also has ribonuclease activity that degrades the viral RNA during the synthesis of cDNA, as well as DNA-dependent DNA polymerase activity that copies the sense cDNA strand into an *antisense* DNA to form a double-stranded viral DNA intermediate (vDNA).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The HIV viral RNA structural elements regulate the progression of reverse transcription.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Self-replicating stretches of eukaryotic genomes known as retrotransposons utilize reverse transcriptase to move from one position in the genome to another via an RNA intermediate.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] They are found abundantly in the genomes of plants and animals.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Telomerase is another reverse transcriptase found in many eukaryotes, including humans, which carries its own RNA template; this RNA is used as a template for DNA replication.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Initial reports of reverse transcriptase in prokaryotes came as far back as 1971 in France (Beljanski et al., 1971a, 1972) and a few years later in the USSR (Romashchenko 1977).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] These have since been broadly described as part of bacterial Retrons, distinct sequences that code for reverse transcriptase, and are used in the synthesis of msDNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In order to initiate synthesis of DNA, a primer is needed.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In bacteria, the primer is synthesized during replication.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Valerian Dolja of Oregon State argues that viruses, due to their diversity, have played an evolutionary role in the development of cellular life, with reverse transcriptase playing a central role.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The reverse transcriptase employs a "right hand" structure similar to that found in other viral nucleic acid polymerases.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In addition to the transcription function, retroviral reverse transcriptases have a domain belonging to the RNase H family, which is vital to their replication.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] By degrading the RNA template, it allows the other strand of DNA to be synthesized.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Some fragments from the digestion also serve as the primer for the DNA polymerase (either the same enzyme or a host protein), responsible for making the other (plus) strand.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] There are three different replication systems during the life cycle of a retrovirus.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The first process is the reverse transcriptase synthesis of viral DNA from viral RNA, which then forms newly made complementary DNA strands.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The second replication process occurs when host cellular DNA polymerase replicates the integrated viral DNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Lastly, RNA polymerase II transcribes the proviral DNA into RNA, which will be packed into virions.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Mutation can occur during one or all of these replication steps.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase has a high error rate when transcribing RNA into DNA since, unlike most other DNA polymerases, it has no proofreading ability.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] This high error rate allows mutations to accumulate at an accelerated rate relative to proofread forms of replication.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The commercially available reverse transcriptases produced by Promega are quoted by their manuals as having error rates in the range of 1 in 17,000 bases for AMV and 1 in 30,000 bases for M-MLV.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Other than creating single-nucleotide polymorphisms, reverse transcriptases have also been shown to be involved in processes such as transcript fusions, exon shuffling and creating artificial antisense transcripts.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] It has been speculated that this *template switching* activity of reverse transcriptase, which can be demonstrated completely *in vivo*, may have been one of the causes for finding several thousand unannotated transcripts in the genomes of model organisms.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Two RNA genomes are packaged into each retrovirus particle, but, after an infection, each virus generates only one provirus.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] After infection, reverse transcription is accompanied by template switching between the two genome copies (copy choice recombination).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] There are two models that suggest why RNA transcriptase switches templates.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The first, the forced copy-choice model, proposes that reverse transcriptase changes the RNA template when it encounters a nick, implying that recombination is obligatory to maintaining virus genome integrity.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The second, the dynamic choice model, suggests that reverse transcriptase changes templates when the RNAse function and the polymerase function are not in sync rate-wise, implying that recombination occurs at random and is not in response to genomic damage.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] A study by Rawson et al. supported both models of recombination.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] From 5 to 14 recombination events per genome occur at each replication cycle.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Template switching (recombination) appears to be necessary for maintaining genome integrity and as a repair mechanism for salvaging damaged genomes.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] All known natural reverse transcriptases evolved from an ancestor that has no proofreading ability, causing the aforementioned low fidelity.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] In 2016, scientists successfully used directed evolution to modify the proofreading *Tko* DNA polymerase into what they call a *reverse transcribing xenotranscriptase* (RTX).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] This new enzyme is able to copy from and proofread with RNA *and* DNA templates.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] It is expected to improve the accuracy in RNA sequencing and other forms of RT-PCR.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] As HIV uses reverse transcriptase to copy its genetic material and generate new viruses (part of a retrovirus proliferation circle), specific drugs have been designed to disrupt the process and thereby suppress its growth.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Collectively, these drugs are known as reverse-transcriptase inhibitors and include the nucleoside and nucleotide analogues zidovudine (trade name Retrovir), lamivudine (Epivir) and tenofovir (Viread), as well as non-nucleoside inhibitors, such as nevirapine (Viramune).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase is commonly used in research to apply the polymerase chain reaction technique to RNA in a technique called reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR).
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The classical PCR technique can be applied only to DNA strands, but, with the help of reverse transcriptase, RNA can be transcribed into DNA, thus making PCR analysis of RNA molecules possible.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] Reverse transcriptase is used also to create cDNA libraries from mRNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The commercial availability of reverse transcriptase greatly improved knowledge in the area of molecular biology, as, along with other enzymes, it allowed scientists to clone, sequence, and characterise RNA.
[src:prime-editing/reverse-transcriptase] The aforementioned RTx reverse transcriptase is commercially available.
